#compdef shards
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# crystal-lang/shards src/cli.cr (**Crystal language**
# stdlib **OptionParser**; corpus's first documented
# Crystal CLI):
#   src/cli.cr line 1 (`require "option_parser"`)
#   src/cli.cr lines 5-17 (BUILTIN_COMMANDS array literal:
#     11 subcommands)
#   src/cli.cr lines 19-40 (display_help_and_exit fn with
#     embedded heredoc help text)
#   src/cli.cr lines 42-135 (Shards.run main fn with
#     `OptionParser.parse(cli_options) do |opts|` block-
#     DSL setup)
#   src/cli.cr lines 48-72 (12 `opts.on(...)` flag
#     declarations — block-handler-per-flag pattern)
#   src/cli.cr lines 74-133 (`opts.unknown_args do |args,
#     options|` block — handles positional args +
#     subcommand routing)
#   src/cli.cr lines 124-129 (EXTERNAL SUBCOMMAND
#     DISCOVERY: if the command isn't a builtin, tries
#     to exec `shards-<command>` from PATH —
#     cargo/git-extension style)
#   src/cli.cr lines 137-145 (cli_options fn: merges
#     `ARGV` with `ENV.fetch("SHARDS_OPTS", "")` env
#     var; uses Crystal MACRO `{% if compare_versions(...)
#     %}` for compile-time version branching)
#   src/cli.cr lines 154-167 (parse_args helper: splits
#     trailing args into (positionals, dash-prefixed
#     options) — handcrafted argv-massage for `build` /
#     `run` subcommand pass-through)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# shards is the **Crystal language package manager** —
# the equivalent of Ruby's bundler / Rust's cargo /
# JavaScript's npm for Crystal projects.  Pivots from
# Python Typer (R268) into the **Crystal language
# tooling cluster**.  Sister to crystal (the Crystal
# compiler; binary in `crystal-lang` org; check existing).
# **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented
# Crystal CLI** — adds a new language to the cross-
# language CLI taxonomy.
#
# Critical extraction note: shards uses **Crystal stdlib
# `OptionParser`** at `require "option_parser"` — corpus's
# **first documented Crystal CLI** (every prior corpus
# CLI was Rust/Go/Python/Ruby/C/C++/Shell).  Extends the
# **cross-language CLI taxonomy**: (a) Rust clap derive
# (R247-R262, R268), (b) Rust clap builder (R259), (c)
# Rust clap v3 (R261), (d) Go cobra (multiple), (e) Go
# pflag (multiple), (f) Go flaggy (R263), (g) Go stdlib
# flag (R264, R265), (h) Python Click (R266), (i) Python
# argparse (R267), (j) Python Typer (R268), (k) **Crystal
# OptionParser** (R269 — NEW).  Crystal's OptionParser
# is **block-DSL-based** — each flag is declared with a
# `opts.on(...) { ... }` call where the block is the
# handler.  Distinct from Rust clap's declarative
# struct/enum approach and from Python Click's decorator
# stack.  Crystal's idiom: imperative flag construction
# inside a `parse do |opts| ... end` block, with each
# flag's behavior expressed as a closure.
#
# Critical extraction note: shards uses **`opts.on("--jobs=N",
# "...") { |n| self.jobs = n.to_i }`** at cli.cr:67 — the
# value-taking flag pattern in Crystal OptionParser:
# `=N` in the flag spec means "this flag takes a value
# named N"; the block receives the value as a string;
# the block must do its own type conversion (`.to_i`).
# Documents the **block-receives-string + manual-cast
# pattern** — Crystal's OptionParser does NOT auto-
# convert types (unlike argparse's `type=int`).  Plus
# the metavar `N` shown in `--help` output is just for
# documentation — no enforcement.  Distinct from R266
# uvicorn's Click `type=int` (auto-convert) and R260
# dua's `pub threads: usize` (Rust auto-convert via
# clap's ValueParser).
#
# Critical extraction note: shards uses **`opts.unknown_args
# do |args, options| ... end`** at cli.cr:74-133 — the
# block-DSL for handling **non-flag positional arguments**.
# Crystal OptionParser separates "known" flags
# (declared via `opts.on(...)`) from "unknown_args" (the
# rest).  The block receives both `args` (positionals
# in order) and `options` (the original flag list).
# shards uses this to ROUTE TO SUBCOMMANDS: `args[0]?`
# is the subcommand name; `args[1..-1]` are the
# subcommand's args.  Documents the **unknown_args-for-
# subcommand-routing pattern** — Crystal OptionParser
# has no built-in subcommand support, so subcommand
# dispatch is done via this block.  Distinct from clap
# derive's `#[clap(subcommand)]` enum (auto-routes) and
# from Click's `@click.group()` (auto-routes).
#
# Critical extraction note: shards uses **EXTERNAL
# SUBCOMMAND DISCOVERY** at cli.cr:124-129 — if the
# given subcommand isn't in BUILTIN_COMMANDS, shards
# tries to find `shards-<subcommand>` on `$PATH` via
# `Process.find_executable(program_name)`.  If found,
# it execs the external binary with the full ARGV.
# Documents the **plugin-style subcommand pattern** —
# corpus's first documented occurrence (well-known in
# the wild: git extensions, cargo subcommands, gh
# extensions).  Distinct from clap derive's
# `#[command(external_subcommand)]` attribute (which
# auto-handles this) — shards implements the discovery
# manually.  Documents the **2 external-subcommand
# patterns**: (a) declarative via clap attribute, (b)
# manual via `find_executable` + `exec`.  Adding a new
# subcommand to shards is as simple as putting a
# `shards-foo` binary on PATH.
#
# Critical extraction note: shards uses **`SHARDS_OPTS`
# env var as additional CLI options source** at
# cli.cr:140 — `ENV.fetch("SHARDS_OPTS", "").split`
# (or `Process.parse_arguments(...)` in Crystal 1.0+)
# returns a list of extra flags that get appended to
# `ARGV.dup`.  So `SHARDS_OPTS="--no-color --jobs=4"
# shards install` is equivalent to `shards --no-color
# --jobs=4 install`.  Documents the **env-var-as-extra-
# argv pattern** — distinct from R252 saya's per-flag
# `env =` (Rust auto-bind one env var per flag) and
# R266 uvicorn's `auto_envvar_prefix` (Click auto-bind
# per option).  Shards' approach is a SINGLE env var
# that contributes MULTIPLE flags via splitting.
# Useful when users want to set a constant set of
# preferences once.  Corpus's **first documented single-
# env-var-as-argv-additions pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: shards uses **Crystal MACROS
# at compile time** at cli.cr:139-143 — `{% if
# compare_versions(Crystal::VERSION, "1.0.0-0") > 0 %}
# ... {% else %} ... {% end %}` is a COMPILE-TIME
# version check that selects between two code paths
# depending on the Crystal compiler version.  Documents
# the **Crystal macro compile-time branching** pattern
# — distinct from Rust's `#[cfg(version("1.0"))]` (also
# compile-time) and from runtime version checks.
# Crystal's `{% ... %}` is the macro syntax; the chosen
# branch is interpolated into the compiled code.  Plus
# the use of `Process.parse_arguments(...)` is itself a
# Crystal 1.0+ feature.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1

# 11 BUILTIN_COMMANDS decoded source-direct from
# cli.cr:5-17.
local -a subcommands=(
  'build:build specified targets in `bin` (delegates build_options to `crystal build`)'
  'run:build and run specified target'
  'check:verify all dependencies are installed'
  'init:initialize a `shard.yml` file'
  'install:install dependencies (creates/uses `shard.lock`)'
  'list:list installed dependencies (--tree for tree view)'
  'lock:lock dependencies in `shard.lock` (does not install)'
  'outdated:list outdated dependencies (--pre for pre-releases)'
  'prune:remove unused dependencies from `lib` folder'
  'update:update dependencies and `shard.lock`'
  'version:print current version of the shard (takes optional path)'
)

# 12 global flags decoded source-direct from
# cli.cr:48-72.
local -a global_flags=(
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print usage synopsis]'
  '--version[print the shards version]'
  '--no-color[disable colored output]'
  '--frozen[strictly install locked versions from shard.lock]'
  '--without-development[do not install development dependencies]'
  '--production[shortcut for --frozen --without-development]'
  '--skip-postinstall[do not run postinstall of dependencies]'
  '--skip-executables[do not install executables]'
  '--local[do not update remote repos; use local cache only]'
  '--jobs=[number of parallel repo downloads (default: 8; git only; OptionParser block-receives-string + manual .to_i cast)]:n:'
  '--ignore-crystal-version[has no effect (compat; will be removed)]'
  '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[increase log verbosity (print debug statements)]'
  '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[decrease log verbosity (warnings + errors only)]'
)

_arguments -C \
  $global_flags \
  '1:subcommand:->subcmd' \
  '*::args:->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcmd)
    _describe -t subcommands 'shards subcommand (or external `shards-<cmd>` plugin)' subcommands && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $words[1] in
      build|run)
        # build/run delegate trailing args to
        # `crystal build` via parse_args helper.
        _arguments \
          $global_flags \
          '*:target or crystal build option:' && ret=0
        ;;
      check|init|install|prune)
        # No additional flags beyond globals.
        _arguments $global_flags && ret=0
        ;;
      list)
        _arguments \
          $global_flags \
          '--tree[show installed dependencies as a tree]' && ret=0
        ;;
      lock)
        _arguments \
          $global_flags \
          '--update[update lock file even if shards are present]' \
          '--print[print to stdout instead of writing to shard.lock]' \
          '*:shard name:' && ret=0
        ;;
      outdated)
        _arguments \
          $global_flags \
          '--pre[include pre-release versions]' && ret=0
        ;;
      update)
        _arguments \
          $global_flags \
          '*:shard name to update:' && ret=0
        ;;
      version)
        _arguments \
          $global_flags \
          '1:shard path (default: current dir):_files -/' && ret=0
        ;;
      *)
        # Unknown subcommand falls through to external
        # `shards-<command>` discovery via
        # Process.find_executable.  We can't predict
        # external subcommand args.
        _files && ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
